snippet.textDisplay:
Geneva Convention on Certain Conventional Weapons
Protocol IV
Article 1
"It is prohibited to employ laser weapons specifically designed, as their sole combat function or as one of their combat functions, to cause permanent blindness to unenhanced vision, that is to the naked eye or to the eye with corrective eyesight devices. The High Contracting Parties shall not transfer such weapons to any State or non-State entity."

I can imagine a weapon that can "set skin on fire" would also do permanent damage to the eyes, even though the laser beams are invisible...
Saying "this is not one of their designed combat functions" is like saying "killing civilians is not one of the designed combat funktions of an M4", so no, I wouldn't consider that a valid argument.
